<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1290,1783]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1290,1315]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Forewing medium sized; trichosors present; crossveins poorly preserved in wings of all specimens; costal area with veinlets widely spaced, mostly simple; subcostal area with 
<emphasis box="[995,1039,1327,1350]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">sc-r</emphasis>
crossveins not detected; crossveins in area between RA and RP few or absent (one detected in one specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Riek" authorityYear="1955" box="[1029,1147,1362,1387]" class="Insecta" family="Neuroptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Lithosmylidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvula">
<emphasis box="[1029,1147,1362,1387]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">L. parvula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); RP originating close to wing base, with at least 10 branches, very slightly sinuous distally in some species; crossveins of RP field not well preserved in most material, but apparently restricted to a few random ones proximally and two widely separate and irregular gradate series; M forked close to wing base; CuA irregularly pectinate forked, with branches oblique. CuP dichotomously forked with few branches; 1A pectinate, length variable; 2A deeply forked; 3A short and apparently simple; HW unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1290,1783]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1578,1603]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Comments</emphasis>
. A specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Riek" authorityYear="1955" box="[510,617,1578,1603]" class="Insecta" family="Neuroptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Lithosmylidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lineata">
<emphasis box="[510,617,1578,1603]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">L. lineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was considered by 
<bibRefCitation author="Riek" box="[836,969,1578,1603]" firstAuthor="Riek" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="654 - 691" refId="ref54007" refString="Riek, E. F. (1955) Fossil insects from the Triassic beds at Mt. Crosby, Queensland. Australian Journal of Zoology, 3, 654 - 691. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / ZO 9550654" type="journal article" year="1955">Riek (1955)</bibRefCitation>
as a hind wing, however 
<bibRefCitation author="Lambkin" box="[1254,1436,1578,1603]" firstAuthor="Lambkin" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="445 - 458" refId="ref50134" refString="Lambkin, K. J. (1988) A re-examination of Lithosmylidia Riek from the Triassic of Queensland with notes on Mesozoic ' osmylid-like' fossil Neuroptera (Insecta: Neuroptera). Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 25, 445 - 458." type="journal article" year="1988">Lambkin (1988)</bibRefCitation>
instead argued that it represented a forewing. Originally, 
<taxonomicName box="[791,945,1614,1639]" class="Insecta" family="Neuroptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Lithosmylidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[791,945,1614,1639]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Lithosmylidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Riek" box="[1153,1288,1614,1639]" firstAuthor="Riek" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="654 - 691" refId="ref54007" refString="Riek, E. F. (1955) Fossil insects from the Triassic beds at Mt. Crosby, Queensland. Australian Journal of Zoology, 3, 654 - 691. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / ZO 9550654" type="journal article" year="1955">Riek (1955)</bibRefCitation>
belonging to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carpenter" authorityYear="1943" box="[151,297,1650,1675]" class="Insecta" family="Osmylidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Kempyninae">Kempyninae</taxonomicName>
, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Makarkin, V. N. &amp; Yang, Q. &amp; Ren, D." box="[355,616,1650,1675]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="209 - 214" refId="ref50998" refString="Makarkin, V. N., Yang, Q. &amp; Ren, D. (2014) A new basal osmylid neuropteran insect from the Middle Jurassic of China linking Osmylidae to the Permian-Triassic Archeosmylidae. Acta Palaeontologica Polonica, 59, 209 - 214." type="journal article" year="2014">
Makarkin 
<emphasis box="[474,532,1650,1675]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
argued that the genus belonged to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Riek" authorityYear="1953" box="[1023,1210,1650,1675]" class="Insecta" family="Archeosmylidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Archeosmylidae</taxonomicName>
. Characters such as Sc+RA joining the wing margin before the wing apex and the lack of RP crossveins support its placement in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Riek" authorityYear="1953" box="[151,338,1722,1747]" class="Insecta" family="Archeosmylidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Archeosmylidae</taxonomicName>
; unfortunately, important information about the hind wing cubital and anal vein fields were not preserved in any specimen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,780,1830,1963]" box="[151,353,1830,1855]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,346,1830,1855]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Included species</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
